In .NET 10, Android enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering (Android 15+), which makes the old `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` non-functional. You now need to react to **window insets** to adjust your layout when the keyboard appears.

### Quick fix — listen to IME insets on Android

**1. In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Ensure edge-to-edge insets are handled
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Bottom padding = keyboard height (or nav bar when keyboard is closed)
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

**2. In `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`**, keep `adjustResize`:

```xml
<activity
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize"
    ... />
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 (old way) | .NET 10 (new way) |
|---|---|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` shrinks the window | Deprecated / no-op in edge-to-edge |
| OS handled layout adjustment | **You** respond to `Ime()` insets and add padding |

### Cross-platform alternative (simpler, less control)

If your chat input is inside a `ScrollView`, MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (on by default) will try to scroll the focused `Entry`/`Editor` into view. For a chat screen this is usually insufficient since you want the **entire input bar + message list** to shift up, which is why the insets approach above is preferred.

### iOS

On iOS this still works automatically via `UIScrollView` keyboard avoidance. No changes needed unless you've disabled safe area handling.
